<DOC><DOCNO> AP880818-0178 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 2057EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Moonshine     08-18 0149</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Moonshine,0154</SECOND><HEAD>Moonshine Deaths Continue in Bombay</HEAD><DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Six more people died Thursday afterdrinking liquor spiked with methanol, bringing the death toll fromrecent poisonings to 32, officials said.   The number is expected to rise because at least 15 other peopleare reported in critical condition at city hospitals.   Two people who allegedly helped make the lethal brew werearrested Thursday, bringing the number in custody in the case to13, said Police Commissioner V.K. Saraf. No charges have been filedyet.   Police in the western state of Maharashtra are looking for theman they believe sold the moonshine, Saraf said.   Bombay, the capital of the western state of Maharashtra, hasmore than 100 illegal distilleries, some large enough to make 220gallons a day.   A bottle of illicit liquor costs the equivalent of 72 cents, orone-sixth the price of regular Indian whiskey.</TEXT></DOC>